\n\nTetrazygia bicolor is a shrub native to Miami-Dade county, the Bahamas and Cuba, generally blooming during the spring and summer months. \n\nThe family (Melastomataceae) is known for its characteristic leaf venation, the cool line work you see on the leaves. These veins play a role in channeling rainwater off the leaves of the tree. \n\nThis adaptation is common in plants throughout the hot, humid, rainy tropics. Water trapped in the crevices of a plant, combined with warm temperatures, make it easy for bacteria and fungus to grow, which could harm the plant. Algae growth in leaves would block sunlight and reduce the plants ability to photosynthesize, so many tropical species deal with this by sporting a waxy coat, and channeling the water off the leaf with a \u201cdrip tip\u201d. \n\n\ud83d\udde3\ufe0f NATURAL INTELLIGENCE \n\nLet\u2019s talk about the beautiful flower. In this video you can see a southern carpenter bee visiting the flower. It changes the pitch of its \u201cbuzz\u201d (wing beats), causing the pollen to be expelled from the anthers (the region of the flower that produces and contains pollen). The filament holds up the anther, extending it up to an accessible part of the flower for pollinators to reach, or for wind to disperse the pollen.\n\nPretty cool huh? \n\nLearn more about these incredible species by booking a tour with us at EVERNPI.org
